# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: combustibility-and-flammability
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] 1-Butanol occurs naturally as a minor product of the ethanol fermentation of sugars and other saccharides and is present in many foods and drinks.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] It is also a permitted artificial flavorant in the United States, used in butter, cream, fruit, rum, whiskey, ice cream and ices, candy, baked goods, and cordials.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] It is also used in a wide range of consumer products.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] The largest use of 1-butanol is as an industrial intermediate, particularly for the manufacture of butyl acetate (itself an artificial flavorant and industrial solvent).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] It is a petrochemical derived from propylene.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Estimated production figures for 1997 are: United States 784,000 tonnes; Western Europe 575,000 tonnes; Japan 225,000 tonnes.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Since the 1950s, most 1-butanol is produced by the hydroformylation of propene (oxo process) to preferentially form the butyraldehyde n-butanal.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Typical catalysts are based on cobalt and rhodium.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Butyraldehyde is then hydrogenated to produce butanol.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] In former times, butanol was prepared from crotonaldehyde, which can be obtained from acetaldehyde.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Butanol can also be produced by fermentation of biomass by bacteria.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Prior to the 1950s, *Clostridium acetobutylicum* was used in industrial fermentation to produce butanol.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Research in the past few decades showed results of other microorganisms that can produce butanol through fermentation.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Butanol can be produced via furan hydrogenation over Pd or Pt catalyst at high temperature and high pressure.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Constituting 85% of its use, 1-butanol is mainly used in the production of varnishes.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] It is a popular solvent, e.g. for nitrocellulose.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] A variety of butanol derivatives are used as solvents, e.g. butoxyethanol or butyl acetate.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Many plasticizers are based on butyl esters, e.g., dibutyl phthalate.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] The monomer butyl acrylate is used to produce polymers.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] 1-Butanol has been proposed as a substitute for diesel fuel and gasoline.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] It is produced in small quantities in nearly all fermentations (see fusel oil).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Clostridium produces much higher yields of butanol.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Research is underway to increase the biobutanol yield from biomass.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Butanol is considered as a potential biofuel (butanol fuel).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Butanol at 85 percent strength can be used in cars designed for gasoline without any change to the engine (unlike 85% ethanol), and it provides more energy for a given volume than ethanol, almost as much as gasoline.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Therefore, a vehicle using butanol would return fuel consumption more comparable to gasoline than ethanol.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Butanol can also be added to diesel fuel to reduce soot emissions.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Butan-1-ol occurs naturally as a result of carbohydrate fermentation in a number of alcoholic beverages, including beer, grape brandies, wine, and whisky.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] It has been detected in the volatiles of hops, jack fruit, heat-treated milks, musk melon, cheese, southern pea seed, and cooked rice.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] 1-Butanol is also formed during deep frying of corn oil, cottonseed oil, trilinolein, and triolein.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Butan-1-ol is one of the "fusel alcohols" (from the German for "bad liquor"), which include alcohols that have more than two carbon atoms and have significant solubility in water.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] It is a natural component of many alcoholic beverages, albeit in low and variable concentrations.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] It (along with similar fusel alcohols) is reputed to be responsible for severe hangovers, although experiments in animal models show no evidence for this.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] The acute toxicity of 1-butanol is relatively low, with oral LD50 values of 790–4,360 mg/kg (rat; comparable values for ethanol are 7,000–15,000 mg/kg).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] It is metabolized completely in vertebrates in a manner similar to ethanol: alcohol dehydrogenase converts 1-butanol to butyraldehyde; this is then converted to butyric acid by aldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Butyric acid can be fully metabolized to carbon dioxide and water by the β-oxidation pathway.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] In the rat, only 0.03% of an oral dose of 2,000 mg/kg was excreted in the urine.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] At sub-lethal doses, 1-butanol acts as a depressant of the central nervous system, similar to ethanol: one study in rats indicated that the intoxicating potency of 1-butanol is about 6 times higher than that of ethanol, possibly because of its slower transformation by alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Liquid 1-butanol, as is common with most organic solvents, is extremely irritating to the eyes; repeated contact with the skin can also cause irritation.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] This is believed to be a generic effect of defatting.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] No skin sensitization has been observed.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] Irritation of the respiratory pathways occurs only at very high concentrations (>2,400 ppm).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] With a flash point of 35 °C, 1-butanol presents a moderate fire hazard: it is slightly more flammable than kerosene or diesel fuel but less flammable than many other common organic solvents.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/1-butanol] The depressant effect on the central nervous system (similar to ethanol intoxication) is a potential hazard when working with 1-butanol in enclosed spaces, although the odour threshold (0.2–30 ppm) is far below the concentration which would have any neurological effect.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] On 7 February 2008, fourteen people were killed and thirty-six injured during a dust explosion at a refinery owned by Imperial Sugar in Port Wentworth, Georgia, United States.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Dust explosions had been an issue of concern among U.S. authorities since three fatal accidents in 2003, with efforts made to improve safety and reduce the risk of reoccurrence.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The Port Wentworth refinery was large and old, featuring outdated construction methods, factors which are believed to have contributed to the fire's severity.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The origin of the explosion was narrowed down to the center of the factory, in a basement located beneath storage silos.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Large accumulations of sugar dust due to poor housekeeping became airborne from the initial shock waves, leading to a series of massive secondary explosions spreading throughout the factory.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Investigations conducted by the Department of Justice ruled out deliberate criminal activity in 2013.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] As a result of the industrial disaster, new safety legislation was proposed.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Port Wentworth's economy declined because the factory had ceased operating.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial intended to rebuild it and return to production by the end of 2008, with replacement buildings to be completed by summer the following year.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Victims filed up to 44 lawsuits for damages against Imperial and/or the company hired to clean up the site.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial said that the explosion was the main reason for a major loss in the first quarter of 2008.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Chemical Safety Board (CSB) released its report on the incident in September 2009, saying that the explosion had been "entirely preventable".
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Investigations by Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives (ATF) reached similar conclusions.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial Sugar's refinery in Port Wentworth, Georgia, was a four-story structure on the bank of the Savannah River.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial, based in Sugar Land, Texas, had bought the refinery and its brand name in 1997 from a previous local owner.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Known since construction as the Dixie Crystal refinery, it was the main employer in Port Wentworth, a town of 3,500, prior to the disaster.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The Port Wentworth refinery was constructed in 1916 by 400 people who were moved from Louisiana specifically for this purpose, and opened the following year.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial bought the refinery together with Savannah Foods to form part of a national supply and distribution network to meet demand from businesses such as Piggly Wiggly, General Mills and Wal-Mart.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] This network was the second largest in the United States.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Workers described the factory as antiquated, with much of the machinery dating back more than twenty-eight years.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The site had continued operating because it had good access to rail and shipping links for transport.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] 90% of the raw sugar supplied to the facility came from overseas in that year, and Imperial expected the "vast majority" to come in from abroad in the year of the explosion as well.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In the time leading up to the explosion, Imperial had run into financial difficulties.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In the fiscal year ending September 30, 2007, sales had fallen eight percent while the company's profits and stock price had fallen by half.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The last two annual reports by Imperial before the explosion said that any damage to the facility at Port Wentworth would "have a material effect on the company's business, financial condition, results of operations and cash flows".
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Meanwhile, in 2004 the CSB conducted a study into the risks presented by dust explosions after three fatal accidents in the year before.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The West Pharmaceutical Services explosion in North Carolina killed six persons, the CTA Acoustics explosion in Kentucky killed seven, and the Hayes Lemmerz explosion in Indiana killed one, prompting the report.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The CSB found that between 1980 and 2005, there had been 281 explosions involving combustible dust, resulting in 119 deaths and 718 injuries.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The agency made a number of recommendations to the Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA), which had been partly implemented by 2008.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The CSB continued to be concerned about the potential for further fatal accidents up until the explosion at the Imperial refinery in Port Wentworth.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The explosion occurred at 7 p.m. local time in what was initially believed to be a room where sugar was bagged by workers.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Witnesses from across the Savannah River in South Carolina reported seeing flames shoot up several stories high.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] There were 112 employees on-site at the time.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The explosion occurred in the center of the refinery, where bagging and storage facilities were fed sugar by a network of elevators and conveyor belts.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Many of the buildings at this location were six to eight stories high with narrow gaps in between.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Ambulances responded to the scene from across twelve counties, and firefighters from three.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The United States Coast Guard closed off the river in the area, and a firefighting tugboat was used to douse the fire from the river.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] A helicopter was used to search the river for anyone who may have been thrown into it by the blast.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Off-duty employees were brought in to assist with search and rescue operations, as emergency services personnel were unfamiliar with the plant's layout.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Red Cross worker Joyce Baker, who was among the first to arrive at the scene, reported that it was like "walking into hell", with some of the men she treated having "no skin at all", while others had skin "just dripping off them".
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The Georgia Emergency Management Agency (GEMHSA) alerted local hospitals to prepare for up to 100 casualties.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] A doctor at nearby Memorial Health Hospital described patients arriving at an emergency triage as varying in condition from suffering minor burns to their hands to having received 80-90 percent burns, with many in critical condition, and one with 95 percent burns.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Many victims were placed in artificial comas because they were on life support systems.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Eight were transported by helicopter to the specialized Joseph M.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Still Burn Center in Augusta, about an hour away.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Five of those injured later died there while receiving treatment.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] A church close to the refinery was used as a point for families seeking information on relatives employed at the facility.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] So many people came that police requested that each family send only one representative.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] At the close of the day of the explosion, six people were missing, with no confirmed deaths.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Overnight, several deep-seated fires were uncovered, and firefighting continued the next day.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Most of the three-mile (5 km) stretch of river that had previously been closed was reopened without restriction, although a patrol remained in place to enforce a safety zone.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The river restrictions delayed one outgoing vessel and two incoming ones.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] There was also a minor oil spill originating from equipment at the refinery's unoccupied and rarely used dock.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The explosion seriously weakened the structure of the refinery, leaving it highly unstable.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The packaging area was totally destroyed; twelve percent of the refinery was demolished by the explosion.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Removal of debris began the day after the accident, with assistance from structural engineers.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The six missing persons were all found dead that day, three of them in tunnels running beneath the facility.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] It was the first major shutdown of a U.S. sugar refinery since American Sugar Refining Inc.'s Domino Sugar shut down its plant in Chalmette, Louisiana, in the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] After seven days, on February 14, 2008, the worst of the fire had been extinguished.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The 100-foot (30 m) sugar storage silos remained alight despite attempts to put the fire out by dousing them with thousands of gallons of water from a helicopter.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Specialist crews and equipment were called in to complete work tackling the smoldering, molten sugar in the silos.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] At this time, seven bodies had been recovered, and an eighth person had died in the hospital.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The location of the explosion was quickly established as a building used to store refined sugar before packaging it and two of three 100-foot (30 m) tall, 18-inch (46 cm) thick reinforced concrete storage silos adjacent to it, as pictured.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] According to Imperial Sugar CEO John Sheptor, the accumulated sugar dust likely acted like gunpowder.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Sheptor, who was in the plant at the time of the explosion, survived only because he was protected by a firewall.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Heavy equipment had to be used to shore up the partially collapsed structure before firefighters could enter it to search for victims.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Within twenty-four hours, the explosive substance was identified as sugar dust.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Federal investigations by OSHA and the CSB were launched, and they interviewed witnesses, checked documentation, and conducted on-scene examination of the plant.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] OSHA arrived within two hours and the CSB within forty-eight hours.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Other brief investigations were conducted by state firefighters and police and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms, and Explosives (ATF), but these were ended quickly after confirming there was no evidence of the explosion and fire having been deliberately started.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In a press conference held on February 17, 2008, one of the six members of the CSB team said that the explosion showed the ongoing risk from dust explosions despite their report highlighting the matter in 2004.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Investigators were unable to enter the silos as OSHA ruled them to be too hazardous after the explosion.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] They were only able to access the area after the silos were demolished.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] By the time this took place, four months after the disaster, investigators believed that the explosion started in a basement area beneath the silos, from which sugar was fed up to the packaging building on conveyor belts.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The factory's outdated construction materials and methods are believed to have contributed to the severity of the blaze.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The ceiling was of wooden tongue and groove design.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The creosote used throughout was known as “fat lighter,” because of the fire risk it posed.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Interviews of Imperial employees conducted by OSHA uncovered a lack of training, as forty of the workers reported never receiving training on how to exit the building in an emergency.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Only five employees recalled having a fire drill.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial's refinery in Louisiana was shut down by the company six weeks after the Port Wentworth disaster, over fears a similar explosion would occur there.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] It was kept from operating for more than a week.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] OSHA fined Imperial $36,000 over safety legislation violations at that plant.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The Georgia plant's 371 workers continued to receive payment from Imperial, and 275 were rehired to assist with cleanup and demolition of parts of the refinery that could not be salvaged.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Work began on April 18, 2008, after Imperial's board confirmed their intention to rebuild.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The plan was for the plant to return to sugar refining by the end of 2008.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Demolition of the sugar silos was conducted on June 24, 2008, with a wrecking ball.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] A replacement packaging building and new sugar silos were intended to be completed by summer 2009.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] During demolition, 2,800,000 pounds (1,300,000 kg) of fire-hardened sugar were recovered from one silo, and another 500,000 pounds (230,000 kg) from the second silo.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The company hoped to recycle the product for ethanol production.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In the first quarter of 2008, Imperial posted a $15.5 million loss, which they said was primarily due to the explosion.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Port Wentworth suffered an economic depression after the accident, with local businesses losing many customers.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial was purchased in 2012 by the Louis Dreyfus Group.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Within a month of the accident, OSHA, fearing that many employers may be unaware their facilities presented a risk of dust explosions, sent a letter to 30,000 employees to alert them to the danger of a similar explosion occurring.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] OSHA also proposed the *Combustible Dust Explosion and Fire Prevention Act of 2008*, a new bill aimed at introducing regulations to reduce the risk of dust explosions.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The bill passed the United States House of Representatives but never passed the United States Senate.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In 2009 OSHA began developing a federal standard for combustible dust.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Congress introduced a bill in 2013 to require OSHA to issue an interim standard based on the voluntary combustible standard set by National Fire Protection Association.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The CSB released its report in September 2009, saying the explosion had been "entirely preventable".
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] It noted that the sugar industry had been aware of the risk of dust explosions since 1926.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Specifically, internal company memorandums by managers in 1967 expressed their concern about the potential of explosions from sugar dust.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Imperial Sugar had made construction changes before the explosion, that enabled the accumulation of sugar dust.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] It had never practiced evacuation procedures, and the lack of emergency lighting meant that people were confined to dark hallways and tunnels at the time of the explosions.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Victims of the disaster continued to file claims against Imperial Sugar and its construction contractor.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] By September 2010, 44 civil suits had been filed in Chatham County Court in relation to the explosion, and eighteen had been settled.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The state appeals court rejected an effort by defendants' attorneys for a pre-trial appeal in two related cases in an effort to limit damages.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In 2011 Lawrence Manker Jr., an Imperial worker who underwent 70 surgeries for burns covering 85% of his body after the plant explosion, settled his lawsuit with the company for an undisclosed amount.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] He was the last victim to leave a hospital burn unit.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In March 2008, Raquel Islas, a female worker whose arms were burnt, sued Savannah-based company Stokes Contracting, which was a contracted construction company.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In April 2008, the widow of Shelathia Harvey also sued Stokes, as well as Savannah Foods, which operated the refinery along with Imperial.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] In August 2008, Malcolm Frazier, who suffered burns over 85% of his body, succumbed to his injuries at the Joseph M.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Still Burn Center, where he had remained since the explosion.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] The United States Department of Labor requested that Ed Tarver, U.S.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Attorney for the Southern District of Georgia, pursue criminal prosecution against Imperial and its executives.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] OSHA cited Imperial with 124 safety violations, finding that the company acted with "plain indifference to, or intentional disregard for, employee safety and health".
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] Tarver said there was not enough evidence of intentional disregard or plain indifference to bring criminal charges against Imperial.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] He also cited a lack of federal criminal laws specifically related to safety in the sugar industry as a reason for his decision.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] OSHA fined Imperial $8.8 million in May 2010 after citing the company for 211 violations at the Port Wentworth plant and the plant in Louisiana.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] After settlement negotiations the company agreed to pay $6 million, while admitting no fault.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/2008-georgia-sugar-refinery-explosion] On February 7, 2009, a monument honoring the people lost in the explosion was dedicated at Legacy Park, on the grounds of the Port Wentworth plant.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone is miscible with water and serves as an important organic solvent in industry, home, and laboratory.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] About 6.7 million tonnes were produced worldwide in 2010, mainly for use as a solvent and for production of methyl methacrylate and bisphenol A, which are precursors to widely used plastics.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] It is a common building block in organic chemistry.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] It serves as a solvent in household products such as nail polish remover and paint thinner.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] It has volatile organic compound (VOC)-exempt status in the United States.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone is produced and disposed of in the human body through normal metabolic processes.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Small quantities of it are present naturally in blood and urine.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] People with diabetic ketoacidosis produce it in larger amounts.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Medical ketogenic diets that increase ketone bodies (acetone, β-hydroxybutyric acid and acetoacetic acid) in the blood are used to suppress epileptic attacks in children with treatment-resistant epilepsy.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] From the 17th century, and before modern developments in organic chemistry nomenclature, acetone was given many different names.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] They included "spirit of Saturn", which was given when it was thought to be a compound of lead and, later, "pyro-acetic spirit" and "pyro-acetic ester".
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Prior to the name "acetone" being coined by French chemists, it was named "mesit" (from the Greek μεσίτης, meaning mediator) by Carl Reichenbach, who also said that methyl alcohol consisted of mesit and ethyl alcohol.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Names derived from mesit include mesitylene and mesityl oxide which were first synthesised from acetone.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] In 1839, the name "acetone" began to be used, because it was obtained from acetic acid.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Unlike many compounds with the *acet-* prefix which have a 2-carbon chain, acetone has a 3-carbon chain.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] That has caused confusion because there can not be a ketone with 2 carbons.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] The prefix refers to acetone's relation to vinegar (*acetum* in Latin, also the source of the words "acid" and "acetic"), rather than its chemical structure.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone was first produced by Andreas Libavius in 1606 by distillation of lead(II) acetate.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] In 1832, French chemist Jean-Baptiste Dumas and German chemist Justus von Liebig determined the empirical formula for acetone.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] In 1833, French chemists Antoine Bussy and Michel Chevreul decided to name acetone by adding the suffix *-one* to the stem of the corresponding acid (viz, acetic acid) just as a similarly prepared product of what was then confused with margaric acid was named margarone.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] By 1852, Alexander William Williamson, an English chemist, realized that acetone was methyl acetyl; the following year, the French chemist Charles Frédéric Gerhardt concurred.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] In 1865, a German chemist, August Kekulé published the modern structural formula for acetone.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Johann Josef Loschmidt had presented the structure of acetone in 1861, but his privately published booklet received little attention.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] During World War I, Chaim Weizmann developed the biochemical process for industrial production of acetone (Weizmann Process).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone is produced directly or indirectly from propene.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Approximately 83% of acetone is produced via the cumene process; as a result, acetone production is tied to phenol production.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Other processes involve the direct oxidation of propylene (Wacker-Hoechst process), or the hydration of propylene to give 2-propanol, which is oxidized (dehydrogenated) to acetone.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Previously, acetone was produced by the dry distillation of acetates, for example calcium acetate in ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] After that time during World War I, acetone was produced using acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation with *Clostridium acetobutylicum* bacteria, which was developed by Chaim Weizmann (later the first president of Israel) in order to help the British war effort, in the preparation of Cordite.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] This acetone-butanol-ethanol fermentation was eventually abandoned when newer methods with better yields were found.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] In 2010, the worldwide production capacity for acetone was estimated at 6.7 million tonnes per year.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] With 1.56 million tonnes per year, the United States had the highest production capacity, followed by Taiwan and China.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] The largest producer of acetone is INEOS Phenol, owning 17% of the world's capacity, with also significant capacity (7–8%) by Mitsui, Sunoco and Shell in 2010.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] INEOS Phenol also owns the world's largest production site (420,000 tonnes/annum) in Beveren, Belgium.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] The spot price of acetone in summer 2011 was 1100–1250 USD/tonne in the United States.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Humans exhale several milligrams of acetone per day and it arises from the decarboxylation of acetoacetate.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Small amounts of acetone are produced in the body by the decarboxylation of ketone bodies.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Certain dietary patterns including prolonged fasting and high-fat low-carbohydrate dieting, can produce ketosis, in which acetone is formed in body tissue.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Certain health conditions, such as alcoholism and diabetes, can produce ketoacidosis, uncontrollable ketosis that leads to a sharp, and potentially fatal, increase in the acidity of the blood.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Since it is a byproduct of fermentation, acetone is a byproduct of the distillery industry.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] It is produced by terrestrial vegetation, undefined ocean processes, incomplete combustion of biomass, or oxidation of hydrocarbons in the atmosphere.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Like most ketones, acetone exhibits the keto–enol tautomerism in which the nominal keto structure (CH3)2C=O of acetone itself is in equilibrium with the enol isomer (CH3)C(OH)=(CH2) (**prop-1-en-2-ol**).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] In acetone vapor at ambient temperature, only 2.4×10−7% of the molecules are in the enol form.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] In the presence of suitable catalysts, two acetone molecules also combine to form the compound diacetone alcohol (CH3)C=O(CH2)C(OH)(CH3)2, which on dehydration gives mesityl oxide (CH3)C=O(CH)=C(CH3)2.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] This product can further combine with another acetone molecule, with loss of another molecule of water, yielding phorone and other compounds.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone is a weak Lewis base that forms adducts with soft acids like I2 and hard acids like phenol.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone also forms complexes with divalent metals.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Under ultraviolet light, acetone fluoresces.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] The flame temperature of pure acetone is 1980 °C.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] At its melting point (−96 °C) is claimed to polymerize to give a white elastic solid, soluble in acetone, stable for several hours at room temperature.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] To do so, a vapor of acetone is co-condensed with magnesium as a catalyst onto a very cold surface.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] The outcome of irradiation of acetone is wavelength dependent.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] The latter process is relevant to the atmospheric chemistry of acetone.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone can then be metabolized either by CYP2E1 via methylglyoxal to D-lactate and pyruvate, and ultimately glucose/energy, or by a different pathway via propylene glycol to pyruvate, lactate, acetate (usable for energy) and propionaldehyde.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] About a third of the world's acetone is used as a solvent, and a quarter is consumed as acetone cyanohydrin, a precursor to methyl methacrylate.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone is used to synthesize methyl methacrylate.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] The third major use of acetone (about 20%) is synthesizing bisphenol A.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Bisphenol A is a component of many polymers such as polycarbonates, polyurethanes, and epoxy resins.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Many millions of kilograms of acetone are consumed in the production of the solvents methyl isobutyl alcohol and methyl isobutyl ketone.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] These products arise via an initial aldol condensation to give diacetone alcohol.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Condensation with acetylene gives 2-methylbut-3-yn-2-ol, precursor to synthetic terpenes and terpenoids.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone is a good solvent for many plastics and some synthetic fibers.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] It is used for thinning polyester resin, cleaning tools used with it, and dissolving two-part epoxies and superglue before they harden.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] It is used as one of the volatile components of some paints and varnishes.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Although itself flammable, acetone is used extensively as a solvent for the safe transportation and storage of acetylene, which cannot be safely pressurized as a pure compound.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Vessels containing a porous material are first filled with acetone followed by acetylene, which dissolves into the acetone.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] One litre of acetone can dissolve around 250 litres of acetylene at a pressure of 10 bars (1.0 MPa).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone is used as a solvent by the pharmaceutical industry and as a denaturant in denatured alcohol.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone is also present as an excipient in some pharmaceutical drugs.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] A variety of organic reactions employ acetone as a polar, aprotic solvent, e.g. the Jones oxidation.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Because acetone is cheap, volatile, and dissolves or decomposes with most laboratory chemicals, an acetone rinse is the standard technique to remove solid residues from laboratory glassware before a final wash.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Despite common desiccatory use, acetone dries only via bulk displacement and dilution.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] It forms no azeotropes with water (see azeotrope tables).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone also removes certain stains from microscope slides.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] An acetone/dry ice mixture cools many low-temperature reactions.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Make-up artists use acetone to remove skin adhesive from the netting of wigs and mustaches by immersing the item in an acetone bath, then removing the softened glue residue with a stiff brush.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone is a main ingredient in many nail polish removers because it breaks down nail polish.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] It is used for all types of nail polish removal, like gel nail polish, dip powder and acrylic nails.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] The chemical modifies peptides, both at α- or ε-amino groups, and in a poorly understood but rapid modification of certain glycine residues.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] In pathology, acetone helps find lymph nodes in fatty tissues (such as the mesentery) for tumor staging.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] The liquid dissolves the fat and hardens the nodes, making them easier to find.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Dermatologists use acetone with alcohol for acne treatments to chemically peel dry skin.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Common agents used for chemical peeling are salicylic acid, glycolic acid, azelaic acid, 30% salicylic acid in ethanol, and trichloroacetic acid (TCA).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Prior to chemexfoliation, the skin is cleaned and excess fat removed in a process called defatting, using acetone, hexachlorophene, or a combination of these agents.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone has been shown to have anticonvulsant effects in animal models of epilepsy, in the absence of toxicity, when administered in millimolar concentrations.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] It has been hypothesized that the high-fat low-carbohydrate ketogenic diet used clinically to control drug-resistant epilepsy in children works by elevating acetone in the brain.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Because of their higher energy requirements, children have higher acetone production than most adults – and the younger the child, the higher the expected production.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] This indicates that children are not uniquely susceptible to acetone exposure.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] External exposures are small compared to the exposures associated with the ketogenic diet.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone has a relatively long lifetime in the atmosphere of about 2 weeks.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Because of its long lifetime, it can be transported by atmospheric winds to the upper troposphere and lower stratosphere where it can influence hydrogen radical (HOx) production and ozone (O3) levels.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] These two peroxy radicals can then undergo a series of reactions to produce hydrogen oxide radicals (HOx) and can therefore have a significant impact on atmospheric chemistry including concentration of ozone (O3) in the upper troposphere.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Photolysis is just one possible processes that removes acetone from the atmosphere.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone can also be removed by ocean processes and by deposition to dry land surfaces.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] The contributions of each sink to the removal of acetone from the atmosphere is still not fully understood.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone's most hazardous property is its extreme flammability.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] In small amounts, acetone burns with a dull blue flame; in larger amounts, fuel evaporation causes incomplete combustion and a bright yellow flame.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] When above acetone's flash point of −20 °C (−4 °F), air mixtures of 2.5‑12.8% acetone (by volume) may explode or cause a flash fire.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Vapors can flow along surfaces to distant ignition sources and flash back.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Static discharge may ignite acetone vapors, though acetone has a very high ignition initiation energy and accidental ignition is rare.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone's auto-ignition temperature is relatively high 465 °C (869 °F); moreover, auto-ignition temperature depends upon experimental conditions, such as exposure time, and has been quoted as high as 535 °C.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Even pouring or spraying acetone over red-glowing coal will not ignite it, due to the high vapour concentration and the cooling effect of evaporation.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone should be stored away from strong oxidizers, such as concentrated nitric and sulfuric acid mixtures.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] It may explode when stored with chloroform in the presence of a base.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] When oxidized without combustion, for example with hydrogen peroxide, acetone may form acetone peroxide, a highly unstable primary explosive.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone peroxide may be formed accidentally, e.g. when waste peroxide is poured into waste solvents.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone occurs naturally as part of certain metabolic processes in the human body, and has been studied extensively and is believed to exhibit only slight toxicity in normal use.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] There is no strong evidence of chronic health effects if basic precautions are followed.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] It is generally recognized to have low acute and chronic toxicity if ingested and/or inhaled.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone is not regarded as a carcinogen, a mutagen, or a concern for chronic neurotoxicity effects.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone can be found as an ingredient in a variety of consumer products ranging from cosmetics to processed and unprocessed foods.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] The United States Food and Drug Administration rates acetone as a generally recognized as safe (GRAS) substance when present in food and drink at concentrations from 5 to 8 mg/L.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acetone is an irritant, causing mild skin and moderate-to-severe eye irritation.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Like many other solvents, acetone may depress the central nervous system at high vapor concentrations.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] Acute toxicity for mice by ingestion (LD50) is 3 g/kg, and by inhalation (LC50) is 44 g/m3 over 4 hours.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] In 1995, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) removed acetone from the list of volatile organic compounds.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] In making its decision EPA conducted an extensive review of the available toxicity data on acetone, which was continued through the 2000s.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acetone] It found that the evaluable "data are inadequate for an assessment of the human carcinogenic potential of acetone".
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Modacrylic is a modified acrylic fiber that contains at least 35% and at most 85% acrylonitrile.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Vinylidene chloride or vinyl bromide used in modacrylic give the fiber flame retardant properties.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] End-uses of modacrylic include faux fur, wigs, hair extensions, and protective clothing.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] The polymer is formed by free-radical polymerization in aqueous suspension.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Washing, stretching, drying, and crimping complete the processing.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Acrylic fibers are produced in a range of deniers, usually from 0.9 to 15, as cut staple or as a 500,000 to 1 million filaments tow.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] End uses include sweaters, hats, hand-knitting yarns, socks, rugs, awnings, boat covers, and upholstery; the fiber is also used as "PAN" precursor for carbon fiber.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Production of acrylic fibers is centered in the Far East, Turkey, India, Mexico, and South America, though a number of European producers still continue to operate, including Dralon and Fisipe.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] US producers have ended production (except for specialty uses such as in friction materials, gaskets, specialty papers, conductive, and stucco), though acrylic tow and staple are still spun into yarns in the USA.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Former U.S. brands of acrylic included Acrilan (Monsanto), and Creslan (American Cyanamid).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Other brand names that are still in use include Dralon (Dralon GmbH) and Drytex (Sudamericana de Fibras, S.A.).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] In the late 1950s, Courtaulds Ltd began investigating the production of an acrylic fiber later to be called "Courtelle" by a process of solvent polymerization.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Methyl acrylate (6%) and acrylonitrile were polymerized in a 50% solution of sodium thiocyanate to produce a dope ready for spinning into a water bath to produce "courtelle" fiber in various grades of denier.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] The sodium thiocyanate solution was reconcentrated and re-used.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] The reaction was a continuous process, with about 5% of reactants being recycled.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] This recycling process resulted in the build-up of pollutants in the process, as did the recycling of the solvent.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] A great deal of research in the chemical engineering laboratory in Lockhurst Lane, Coventry, and on the pre-production pilot plant at Little Heath overcame the recycling problems.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] It resulted in the process becoming a commercial success at a new production plant in Grimsby.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Acrylic is lightweight, soft, and warm, with a wool-like feel.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] It can also be made to mimic other fibers, such as cotton, when spun on short staple equipment.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Some acrylic is extruded in colored or pigmented form; others are extruded in "ecru", otherwise known as "natural," "raw white," or "undyed." Pigmented fiber has the highest color permanence.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Its fibers are very resilient compared to both other synthetics and natural fibers.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Some acrylic is used in clothing as a less expensive alternative to cashmere, due to the similar feeling of the materials.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Some acrylic fabrics may fuzz or pill easily, though there are low-pilling variants.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Acrylic takes color well, is washable, and is generally hypoallergenic.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] End-uses include socks, hats, gloves, scarves, sweaters, home furnishing fabrics, and awnings.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Acrylic can also be used to make fake fur and to make many different knitted clothes.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] As acrylic is a synthetic fiber, the larvae of clothes moths are unable to digest it.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] However, acrylic fibers that are blended with wool or soiled may be eaten as a consequence of having blended fibers.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Acrylic is the "workhorse" hand-crafting fiber for crafters who knit or crochet; acrylic yarn may be perceived as "cheap" because it is typically priced lower than its natural-fiber counterparts, and because it lacks some of their properties, including softness and propensity to felt.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] The fiber requires heat to "relax" or set the shape of the finished garment, and it is not as warm when wet as alternatives like wool.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Some hand-knitters also complain that the fiber "squeaks" when knitted, or that it is painful to knit with because of a lack of "give" or stretch in the yarn.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] On the other hand, it is machine-washable and extremely color-fast.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] This makes it useful in certain items, like garments for babies, which require constant washing.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] However it is much more flammable than its natural fiber counterparts, so caution should be used when making items for babies and children.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] A team at Plymouth University in the UK spent 12 months analyzing what happened when a number of synthetic materials were washed at different temperatures in domestic washing machines, using different combinations of detergents, to quantify the microfibers shed.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] They found that acrylic was responsible for releasing nearly 730,000 tiny synthetic particles (microplastics) per wash, five times more than polyester-cotton blend fabric, and nearly 1.5 times as many as pure polyester.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Research by ecologist Mark Browne showed synthetic fiber waste over coastlines at a global scale, with the greatest concentration near sewage outflows.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Of the man-made material found on the shoreline, 85% were microfibers and matched the types of material (such as nylon and acrylic) used in clothing.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] In the middle of the 20th century, the DuPont Company (USA) was actively developing a new material that could compete with the then-popular nylon in quality and properties.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] DuPont first introduced this material in 1948 to create a fabric that would be competitive with nylon in its properties.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] This research resulted in the emergence of Orlon, a synthetic fiber isolated from polymers.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] The material turned out to be incredibly practical and, by many characteristics, exceeded many artificial and natural analogs at that time.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] However, the new fabric had a significant disadvantage: the fibers could not be dyed.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Only in 1952, four years later, DuPont chemists solved this problem.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] They created a new version of the previously invented synthetic fabric, which met all the requirements.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] And most importantly, it was perfectly dyed.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] A distinctive feature of the acrylic fiber is its burning behavior; it melts and emits acrid smoke with a sour smell.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/acrylic-fiber] Although acrylic fabric has pros and cons, it is popular in the fashion and textile world due to its characteristics.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] An **apartment** (North American English), **flat** (British English, Indian English, South African English) or **unit** (Australian English), is a self-contained housing unit that occupies part of a building.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The housing tenure of apartments also varies considerably, from large-scale public housing, to owner occupancy within what is legally a condominium (strata title or commonhold) or leasehold, to tenants renting from a private landlord.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The buildings that contain apartments may be called different things depending on size or country (see below).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The term *apartment* is favoured in North America (although in some Canadian cities, *flat* is used for a unit which is part of a house containing two or three units, typically one to a floor).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In the UK and Australia, *flat* is the common term, although parts of the real estate industry has recently began using the term "apartment" for large upmarket flats, especially if their target group is foreign investors.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In some countries, the word "unit" is a more general term referring to both apartments and rental business suites.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The word 'unit' is generally used only in the context of a specific building.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] "Mixed-use buildings" combine commercial and residential uses within the same structure.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Typically, mixed-use buildings consist of businesses on the lower floors (often retail in street-facing ground floor and supporting subterranean levels) and residential apartments on the upper floors.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Tenement law refers to the feudal basis of permanent property such as land or rents.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] It may be found combined as in "Messuage or Tenement" to encompass all the land, buildings and other assets of a property.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Most apartments are in buildings designed for the purpose, but large older houses are sometimes divided into apartments.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The word *apartment* denotes a residential unit or section in a building.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In some locations, particularly the United States, the word connotes a rental unit owned by the building owner, and is not typically used for a condominium.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In England and Wales, some flat owners own shares in the company that owns the freehold of the building as well as holding the flat under a lease.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] This arrangement is commonly known as a "share of freehold" flat.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The freehold company has the right to collect annual ground rents from each of the flat owners in the building.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The freeholder can also develop or sell the building, subject to the usual planning and restrictions that might apply.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] This situation does not happen in Scotland, where long leasehold of residential property was previously unusual and now is impossible.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Apartment buildings are multi-story buildings where three or more residences are contained within one structure.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Such a building may be called an *apartment building*, *apartment complex*, *flat complex*, *block of flats*, *tenement* (Scotland),*tower block*, *high-rise* or, occasionally, *mansion block* (in British English), especially if it consists of many apartments for rent.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] A high-rise apartment building is commonly referred to as a *residential tower*, *apartment tower*, or *block of flats* in Australia.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] A high-rise building is defined by its height differently in various jurisdictions.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] It may be only residential, in which case it might also be called a tower block, or it might include other functions such as hotels, offices, or shops.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] There is no clear difference between a tower block and a skyscraper, although a building with fifty or more stories is generally considered a skyscraper.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] High-rise buildings became possible with the invention of the elevator (lift) and cheaper, more abundant building materials.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Their structural system usually is made of reinforced concrete and steel.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] A low-rise building and mid-rise buildings have fewer stories, but the limits are not always clear.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Emporis defines a low-rise as "an enclosed structure below 35 metres [115 feet] which is divided into regular floor levels." The city of Toronto defines a mid-rise as a building between 4 and 12 stories.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Garden apartment buildings are usually one or two storey structures where the individual apartments open directly to the outdoors and where the building or complex offers landscaped grounds.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In American English, the distinction between rental apartments and condominiums is that while rental buildings are owned by a single entity and rented out to many, condominiums are owned individually, while their owners still pay a monthly or yearly fee for building upkeep.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Condominiums are often leased by their owner as rental apartments.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] A third alternative, the cooperative apartment building (or "co-op"), acts as a corporation with all of the tenants as shareholders of the building.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Tenants in cooperative buildings do not own their apartment, but instead own a proportional number of shares of the entire cooperative.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] As in condominiums, cooperators pay a monthly fee for building upkeep.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Co-ops are common in cities such as New York, and have gained some popularity in other larger urban areas in the U.S.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In British English the usual word is "flat", but *apartment* is used by property developers to denote expensive "flats" in exclusive and expensive residential areas in, for example, parts of London such as Belgravia and Hampstead.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In Scotland, it is called a block of flats or, if it is a traditional sandstone building, a *tenement*, a term which has a negative connotation elsewhere.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In India and South Africa, the words "flat" and "apartment" are interchangeably used to refer to a housing unit in a building.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The word "flat" is also used to refer to multi-story dwellings that have lifts.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Australian English and New Zealand English traditionally used the term *flat* (although it also applies to any rental property), and more recently also use the terms *unit* or *apartment*.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In Australia, a 'unit' refers to flats, apartments or even semi-detached houses.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In Australia, the terms "unit", "flat" and "apartment" are largely used interchangeably.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Newer high-rise buildings are more often marketed as "apartments", as the term "flats" carries colloquial connotations.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The term condominium or condo is rarely used in Australia despite attempts by developers to market it.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In Malaysian English, *flat* often denotes a housing block of two rooms with walk-up, no lift, without facilities, typically five stories tall, and with outdoor parking space, while *apartment* is more generic and may also include luxury condominiums.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In Japanese English loanwords (*Wasei-eigo*), the term *apartment* (アパート *apaato*) is used for lower-income housing and *mansion* (マンション *manshon*) is used for high-end apartments; but both terms refer to what English-speakers regard as an apartment.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] This use of the term *mansion* has a parallel with British English's *mansion block*, a term denoting prestigious apartment buildings from the Victorian and Edwardian, which usually feature an ornate facade and large, high-ceilinged flats with period features.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] *Danchi* is the Japanese word for a large cluster of apartment buildings of a particular style and design, typically built as public housing by government authorities.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The smallest self-contained apartments are referred to as studio, efficiency or bachelor apartments in the US and Canada, or studio flat in the UK.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] These units usually consist of a large single main room which acts as the living room, dining room and bedroom combined and usually also includes kitchen facilities, with a separate bathroom.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In Korea, the term "one room" (*wonroom*) refers to a studio apartment.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] A bedsit is a UK variant on single room accommodation: a bed-sitting room, probably without cooking facilities, with a shared bathroom.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] A bedsit is not self-contained and so is not an apartment or flat as this article uses the terms; it forms part of what the UK government calls a house in multiple occupation.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The American variant of the bedsit is the single room occupancy.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Merriam-Webster defines a garden apartment in American English as "a multiple-unit low-rise dwelling having considerable lawn or garden space." The apartment buildings are often arranged around courtyards that are open at one end.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Such a garden apartment shares some characteristics of a townhouse: each apartment has its own building entrance, or shares that entrance via a staircase and lobby that adjoins other units immediately above and/or below it.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Unlike a townhouse, each apartment occupies only one level.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Such garden apartment buildings are almost never more than three stories high, since they typically lack elevators.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] However, the first "garden apartment" buildings in New York, US, built in the early 1900s, were constructed five stories high.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Some garden apartment buildings place a one-car garage under each apartment.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The interior grounds are often landscaped.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In Chicago, a garden apartment refers to a basement apartment.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The *Oxford English Dictionary* defines the use of "garden flat" in British English as "a basement or ground-floor flat with a view of and access to a garden or lawn", although its citations acknowledge that the reference to a garden may be illusory.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] "Garden flat" can serve simply as a euphemism for a basement.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The large Georgian or Victorian townhouse was built with an excavated subterranean space around its front known as an area, often surrounded by cast iron railings.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] This lowest floor housed the kitchen, the main place of work for the servants, with a "tradesman's entrance" via the area stairs.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] This "lower ground floor" (another euphemism) has proven ideal for conversion to a self-contained "garden flat".
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] One American term for this arrangement is an English basement.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Generally on the lowest (below ground) floor of a building.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] A unit in the attic of a building and usually converted from domestic servants' quarters.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] These apartments are characterized by their sloping walls, which can restrict the usable space; the resultant stair climb in buildings that do not have elevators and the sloping walls can make garret apartments less desirable than units on lower floors.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] However, because these apartments are located on the top floors of their buildings, they can offer the best views and are quieter because of the lack of upstairs neighbours.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In Canada these are commonly located below the main house and are therefore "basement suites".
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Another term is an "accessory dwelling unit", which may be part of the main house, or a free-standing structure in its grounds.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] It also allows for apartments, even when they are accessed by a corridor, to have windows on both sides of the building.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] A maisonette could encompass Tyneside flats, pairs of single-storey flats within a two-storey terrace.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Their distinctive feature is their use of two separate front doors onto the street, each door leading to a single flat.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] "Maisonette" could also stretch to cottage flats, also known as 'four-in-a-block flats', a style of housing common in Scotland.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The vast majority of apartments are on one level, hence "flat".
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Some, however, have two storeys joined internally by stairs, just like many houses.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] One term for this is "maisonette", as above.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Some housing in the United Kingdom, both public and private, was designed as scissor section flats.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] On a grander level, penthouses may have more than one storey to emphasise the idea of space and luxury.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Two-storey units in new construction are sometimes referred to as "townhouses" in some countries (though not usually in Britain).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] "Duplex" refers to two separate units horizontally adjacent, with a common demising wall, or vertically adjacent, with a floor-ceiling assembly.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Groups of more than two units have corresponding names (Triplex, etc.).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Those buildings that have a third storey are known as triplexes.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In the United States, regional forms have developed, see vernacular architecture.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In Milwaukee, a Polish flat or "raised cottage" is a small house that has been lifted up to accommodate a basement floor housing a separate apartment, then set down again, thus becoming a modest pair of dwellings.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In the Sun Belt, boxy small apartment buildings called dingbats, often with carports below, sprang up from the 1950s.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In the United Kingdom the term *duplex* is usually applied to an apartment with two storeys (with an internal staircase), neither of which is located at ground level.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Such homes are frequently found in low-cost rental housing, in apartment blocks constructed by local authorities, or above street-level retail units, where they may be occupied by the occupier of the retail unit or rented out separately.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Buildings containing two dwellings with a common vertical wall are known as *semi-detached*, or colloquially *semis*.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] This form of construction is very common and built as such rather than being a later conversion.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] This type of apartment developed in the US during the middle of the 20th century.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The term initially described a living space created within a former industrial building, usually 19th century.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] These large apartments found favor with artists and musicians wanting accommodation in large cities (New York for example) and are related to unused buildings in the decaying parts of such cities being occupied illegally by people squatting.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] These loft apartments were usually located in former high-rise warehouses and factories left vacant after town planning rules and economic conditions in the mid 20th century changed.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The resulting apartments created a new bohemian lifestyle and were arranged in a completely different way from most urban living spaces, often including workshops and art studio spaces.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] As the supply of old buildings of a suitable nature has dried up, developers have responded by constructing new buildings in the same aesthetic with varying degrees of success.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] An industrial, warehouse, or commercial space converted to an apartment is commonly called a *loft*, although some modern lofts are built by design.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] A penthouse is an apartment usually located on the top floor of a high-rise apartment building.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] This type of house has exclusive features like private elevators, landscaped terraces, and high ceilings.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In Russia, a communal apartment («коммуналка») is a room with a shared kitchen and bath.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] A typical arrangement is a cluster of five or so room-apartments with a common kitchen and bathroom and separate front doors, occupying a floor in a pre-Revolutionary mansion.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Traditionally a room is owned by the government and assigned to a family on a semi-permanent basis.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] A serviced apartment is any-size space for residential living that includes regular maid and cleaning services provided by the rental agent.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Serviced apartments or serviced flats developed in the early part of the 20th century and were briefly fashionable in the 1920s and 30s.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] They are intended to combine the best features of luxury and self-contained apartments, often being an adjunct of a hotel.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Like guests semi-permanently installed in a luxury hotel, residents could enjoy the additional facilities such as house keeping, laundry, catering and other services if and when desired.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] A feature of these apartment blocks was quite glamorous interiors with lavish bathrooms but no kitchen or laundry spaces in each flat.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] This style of living became very fashionable as many upper-class people found they could not afford as many live-in staff after the First World War and revelled in a "lock-up and leave" life style that serviced apartment hotels supplied.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Some buildings have been subsequently renovated with standard facilities in each apartment, but serviced apartment hotel complexes continue to be constructed.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Recently a number of hotels have supplemented their traditional business model with serviced apartment wings, creating privately owned areas within their buildings - either freehold or leasehold.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Apartments may be available for rent furnished, with furniture, or unfurnished into which a tenant moves in with his own furniture.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Serviced apartments, intended to be convenient for shorter stays, include soft furnishings and kitchen utensils, and maid service.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Laundry facilities may reside in a common area accessible to all building tenants, or each apartment may have its own facilities.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Depending on when the building was built and its design, utilities such as water, heating, and electricity may be common for all of the apartments, or separate for each apartment and billed separately to each tenant.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] (Many areas in the US have ruled it illegal to split a water bill among all the tenants, especially if a pool is on the premises.) Outlets for connection to telephones are typically included in apartments.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Telephone service is optional and is almost always billed separately from the rent payments.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Cable television and similar amenities also cost extra.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Parking space(s), air conditioning, and extra storage space may or may not be included with an apartment.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Rental leases often limit the maximum number of residents in each apartment.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] On or around the ground floor of the apartment building, a series of mailboxes are typically kept in a location accessible to the public and, thus, to the mail carrier.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Every unit typically gets its own mailbox with individual keys to it.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Some very large apartment buildings with a full-time staff may take mail from the carrier and provide mail-sorting service.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Near the mailboxes or some other location accessible by outsiders, a buzzer (equivalent to a doorbell) may be available for each individual unit.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In smaller apartment buildings such as two- or three-flats, or even four-flats, rubbish is often disposed of in trash containers similar to those used at houses.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In larger buildings, rubbish is often collected in a common trash bin or dumpster.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] For cleanliness or minimizing noise, many lessors will place restrictions on tenants regarding smoking or keeping pets in an apartment.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In more urban areas, apartments close to the downtown (British English town- or city-centre area have the benefits of proximity to jobs and/or public transportation.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] However prices per square foot/meter are often much higher than in suburban areas.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Moving up in size from studio flats are one-bedroom apartments, which contain a bedroom enclosed from the other rooms of the apartment, usually by an internal door.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] This is followed by two-bedroom, three-bedroom, etc.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Apartments with more than three bedrooms are rare.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Small apartments often have only one entrance.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Large apartments often have two entrances, perhaps a door in the front and another in the back, or from an underground or otherwise attached parking structure.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Depending on the building design, the entrance doors may be connected directly to the outside or to a common area inside, such as a hallway or a lobby.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The Puebloan peoples of what is now the Southwestern United States have constructed large, multi-room dwellings, some comprising more than 900 rooms, since the 10th century.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In the Classic Period Mesoamerican city of Teotihuacan, apartments were not only the standard means of housing the city's population of over 200,000 inhabitants, but show a remarkably even wealth distribution for the entire city, even by contemporary standards.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Furthermore, the apartments were inhabited by the general populace as a whole, in contrast to other Pre-Modern societies, where apartments were limited to housing the lower class members of the society, as with the somewhat contemporary Roman insulae.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In ancient Rome, the insulae (singular *insula*) were large apartment buildings where the lower and middle classes of Romans dwelled.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The floor at ground level was used for tabernae, shops and businesses, with living space on the higher floors.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Insulae in Rome and other imperial cities reached up to ten or more stories, some with more than 200 stairs.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Several emperors, beginning with Augustus (r.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] 30 BC – 14 AD), attempted to establish limits of 20–25 m for multi-story buildings, but met with only limited success.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The lower floors were typically occupied by either shops or wealthy families, while the upper stories were rented out to the lower classes.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Surviving Oxyrhynchus Papyri indicate that seven-story buildings even existed in provincial towns, such as in 3rd century Hermopolis in Roman Egypt.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] During the medieval Arabic-Islamic period, the Egyptian capital of Fustat (Old Cairo) housed many high-rise residential buildings, some seven stories tall that could reportedly accommodate hundreds of people.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In the 10th century, Al-Muqaddasi described them as resembling minarets, and stated that the majority of Fustat's population lived in these multi-story apartment buildings, each one housing more than 200 people.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In the 11th century, Nasir Khusraw described some of these apartment buildings rising up to fourteen stories, with roof gardens on the top story complete with ox-drawn water wheels for irrigating them.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] By the 16th century, the current Cairo also had high-rise apartment buildings, in which the two lower floors were for commercial and storage purposes and the multiple stories above them were rented out to tenants.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] High-rise apartment buildings were built in the Yemeni city of Shibam in the 16th century.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The houses of Shibam are all made out of mud bricks, but about 500 of them are tower houses, which rise 5 to 11 stories high, with each floor having one or two apartments.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Shibam has been called "Manhattan of the desert".
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Some of them were over 100 feet (30 m) high, thus being the tallest mudbrick apartment buildings in the world to this day.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The Hakka people in southern China adopted communal living structures designed to be easily defensible, in the form of Weilongwu (围龙屋) and Tulou (土楼).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The latter are large, enclosed and fortified earth buildings, between three and five stories high and housing up to eighty families.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In London, by the time of the 2011 census, 52 per cent of all homes were flats.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Many of these were built as Georgian or Victorian houses and subsequently divided up.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Many others were built as council flats.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Many tower blocks were built after the Second World War.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] A number of these have been demolished and replaced with low-rise buildings or housing estates.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, the concept of the flat was slow to catch on amongst the British middle classes, which generally followed the north European standard of single-family houses dating far back into history.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Those who lived in flats were assumed to be lower class and somewhat itinerant, renting for example a "flat above a shop" as part of a lease agreement for a tradesman.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In London and most of Britain, everyone who could afford to do so occupied an entire house—even if this was a small terraced house—while the working poor continued to rent rooms in often overcrowded properties, with one (or more) families per room.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] During the last quarter of the 19th century, as wealth increased, ideas began to change.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Both urban growth and the increase in population meant that more imaginative housing concepts would be needed if the middle and upper classes were to maintain a *pied-à-terre* in the capital.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The traditional London town house was becoming increasingly expensive to maintain.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] For bachelors and unmarried women in particular, the idea of renting a modern mansion flat became increasingly popular.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In Scotland, the term "tenement" lacks the pejorative connotations it carries elsewhere and refers simply to any block of flats sharing a common central staircase and lacking an elevator, particularly those constructed before 1919.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The staircase is informally called a "close" after the historic word for an alleyway.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Tenements were, and continue to be, inhabited by a wide range of social classes and income groups.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Tenements today are bought by a wide range of social types, including young professionals, older retirees, and by absentee landlords, often for rental to students after they leave halls of residence managed by their institution.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The Tenement House is a historic house museum operated by the National Trust for Scotland which offers an insight into the lifestyle of tenement dwellers as it was generations ago.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] During the 19th century, tenements became the predominant type of new housing in Scotland's industrial cities, although they were very common in the Old Town in Edinburgh from the 15th century, where they reached ten or eleven stories and in one case fourteen stories.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Built of sandstone or granite, Scottish tenements are usually three to five stories in height, with two to four flats on each floor.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] (In contrast, industrial cities in England tended to favour "back-to-back" terraces of brick.) Scottish tenements are constructed in terraces, and each entrance within a block is referred to as a *close* or *stair*—both referring to the shared passageway to the individual flats.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Flights of stairs and landings are generally designated common areas, and residents traditionally took turns to sweep clean the floors and, in Aberdeen in particular, took turns to make use of shared laundry facilities in the "back green" (garden or yard).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] It is now more common for cleaning of the common ways to be contracted out through a managing agent or "factor".
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] They were replaced by high-rise blocks that, within a couple of decades, became notorious for crime and poverty.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The Glasgow Corporation made many efforts to improve the situation, most successfully with the City Improvement Trust, which cleared the slums of the old town, replacing them with what they thought of as a traditional high street, which remains an imposing townscape.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] (The City Halls and the Cleland Testimonial were part of this scheme.) National government help was given following World War I when Housing Acts sought to provide "homes fit for heroes".
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Garden suburb areas, based on English models, such as Knightswood, were set up.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] These proved too expensive, so a modern tenement, three stories high, slate roofed and built of reconstituted stone, was re-introduced and a slum clearance programme initiated to clear areas such as the Calton and the Garngad.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] After World War II, more ambitious plans, known as the Bruce Plan, were made for the complete evacuation of slums for modern mid-rise housing developments on the outskirts of the city.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] However, the central government refused to fund the plans, preferring instead to depopulate the city to a series of New Towns.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Again, economic considerations meant that many of the planned "New Town" amenities were never built in these areas.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] These housing estates, known as "schemes", came therefore to be widely regarded as unsuccessful; many, such as Castlemilk, were just dormitories well away from the centre of the city with no amenities, such as shops and public houses ("deserts with windows", as Billy Connolly once put it).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] High-rise living too started off with bright ambition—the Moss Heights, built in the 1950s, are still desirable—but fell prey to later economic pressure.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Many of the later tower blocks were poorly designed and cheaply built and their anonymity caused some social problems.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The demolition of the tower blocks in order to build modern housing schemes has in some cases led to a re-interpretations of the tenement.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In 1970, a team from Strathclyde University demonstrated that the old tenements had been basically sound, and could be given new life with replumbing providing modern kitchens and bathrooms.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The Corporation acted on this principle for the first time in 1973 at the *Old Swan Corner*, Pollokshaws.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Thereafter, *Housing Action Areas* were set up to renovate so-called slums.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Later, privately owned tenements benefited from government help in "stone cleaning", revealing a honey-coloured sandstone behind the presumed "grey" tenemental facades.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The policy of tenement demolition is now considered to have been short-sighted, wasteful and largely unsuccessful.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Many of Glasgow's worst tenements were refurbished into desirable accommodation in the 1970s and 1980s and the policy of demolition is considered to have destroyed fine examples of a "universally admired architectural" style.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The Glasgow Housing Association took ownership of the public housing stock from the city council on 7 March 2003, and has begun a £96 million clearance and demolition programme to clear and demolish many of the high-rise flats.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In 1839, the first New York City tenement was built, and soon they became breeding grounds for outlaws, juvenile delinquents, and organized crime.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Tenements, or their slum landlords, were also known for their price gouging rent.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Many campaigners, such as Upton Sinclair and Jacob Riis, pushed for reforms in tenement dwellings.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] As a result, the New York State Tenement House Act was passed in 1901 to improve the conditions.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Truman signed the Housing Act of 1949 to clean slums and reconstruct housing units for the poor.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The Dakota (1884) was one of the first luxury apartment buildings in New York City.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The majority, however, remained tenements.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Some significant developments in architectural design of apartment buildings came out of the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Among them were groundbreaking designs in Chicago: the 860-880 Lake Shore Drive Apartments (1951), Marina City (1964) and Lake Point Tower (1968).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In the United States, "tenement" is a label usually applied to the less expensive, more basic rental apartment buildings in older sections of large cities.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Many of these apartment buildings are "walk-ups" without an elevator, and some have shared bathing facilities, though this is becoming less common.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The slang term "dingbat" is used to describe cheap urban apartment buildings from the 1950s and 1960s with unique and often wacky façades to differentiate themselves within a full block of apartments.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] They are often built on stilts, and with parking underneath.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Apartments were popular in Canada, particularly in urban centres like Vancouver, Toronto, Ottawa, Montreal, and Hamilton in the 1950s to 1970s.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] By the 1980s, many multi-unit buildings were being constructed as condominiums instead of apartments—both are now very common.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In Toronto and Vancouver, high-rise apartments and condominiums have been spread around the city, giving even the major suburbs a skyline.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The robustness of the condo markets in Toronto and Vancouver are based on the lack of land availability.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The average capitalization rate in the Greater Toronto Area for Q3 2015 hit its lowest level in 30 years: in Q3 2015 it stood at 3.75 per cent, down from 4.2 per cent in Q2 2015 and down almost 50 per cent from the 6.3 per cent posted in Q3 2010.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Apartment buildings in Australia are typically managed by a body corporate in which owners pay a monthly fee to provide for maintenance of common premises.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Many apartments are owned through strata title.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Australian legislation enforces a minimum 2.4 m floor-ceiling height which differentiates apartment buildings from office buildings.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Australia has a relatively recent history in apartment buildings.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Terrace houses were the early response to density development, though the majority of Australians lived in fully detached houses.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Apartments of any kind were legislated against in the Parliament of Queensland as part of the Undue Subdivision of Land Prevention Act 1885.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The earliest apartment buildings were in the major cities of Sydney and Melbourne as the response to fast rising land values–both cities are home to the two oldest surviving apartment buildings in the country, Kingsclere in Potts Point, and The Canterbury Flats in St Kilda.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Melbourne Mansions on Collins Street, Melbourne (now demolished), built in 1906 for mostly wealthy residents is believed by many to be the earliest.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Today the oldest surviving self-contained apartment buildings are in the St Kilda area including the Fawkner Mansions (1910), Majestic Mansions (1912 as a boarding house) and the Canterbury (1914—the oldest surviving buildings contained flats).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Kingsclere, built in 1912 is believed to be the earliest apartment building in Sydney and still survives.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] During the interwar years, apartment building continued in inner Melbourne (particularly in areas such as St Kilda and South Yarra), Sydney (particularly in areas such as Potts Point, Darlinghust and Kings Cross) and in Brisbane (in areas such as New Farm, Fortitude Valley and Spring Hill).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Post–World War II, with the Australian Dream apartment buildings went out of vogue and flats were seen as accommodation only for the poor.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Walk-up flats (without a lift) of two to three stories however were common in the middle suburbs of cities for lower income groups.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The main exceptions were Sydney and the Gold Coast, Queensland where apartment development continued for more than half a century.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In Sydney a limited geography and highly sought after waterfront views (Sydney Harbour and beaches such as Bondi) made apartment living socially acceptable.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Since the 1960s, these cities maintained much higher population densities than the rest of Australia through the acceptance of apartment buildings.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In other cities, apartment building was almost solely restricted to public housing.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Public housing in Australia was common in the larger cities, particularly in Melbourne (by the Housing Commission of Victoria) where a number of high-rise housing commission flats were built between the 1950s and 1970s by successive governments as part of an urban renewal program.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Areas affected included Fitzroy, Flemington, Collingwood, Carlton, Richmond and Prahran.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Similar projects were run in Sydney's lower socio-economic areas like Redfern.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In the 1980s, modern apartment buildings sprang up in riverside locations in Brisbane (along the Brisbane River) and Perth (along the Swan River).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In Melbourne, in the 1990s, a trend began for apartment buildings without the requirement of spectacular views.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] As a continuation of the gentrification of the inner city, a fashion became New York "loft" style apartments (see above) and a large stock of old warehouses and old abandoned office buildings in and around the central business district became the target of developers.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The trend of adaptive reuse extended to conversion of old churches and schools.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Similar warehouse conversions and gentrification began in Brisbane suburbs such as Teneriffe, Queensland and Fortitude Valley and in Sydney in areas such as Ultimo.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] As the supply of buildings for conversion ran out, reproduction and modern high-rise apartments followed.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] This was particularly the case in Melbourne thanks to official planning policies (Postcode 3000), making the CBD the fastest growing, population wise in the country.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Apartment building in the Melbourne metropolitan area has also escalated with the advent of the Melbourne 2030 planning policy.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Urban renewal areas like Docklands, Southbank, St Kilda Road and Port Melbourne are now predominantly apartments.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] There has also been a sharp increase in the number of student apartment buildings in areas such as Carlton in Melbourne.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Despite their size, other smaller cities including Canberra, Darwin, Townsville, Cairns, Newcastle, Wollongong, Adelaide and Geelong have begun building apartments in the 2000s.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Today, residential buildings such as the Eureka Tower and Q1 are among the tallest in the country.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] As of 2019, a majority of Koreans live in apartments.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Since the 1980s, the number of apartment residents has soared, and as the number of apartments has steadily increased, apartments have become a representative form of residence where more than half of the Korean population resides.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] It is the most common house in small and medium-sized cities in Korea, and even these days, apartments are quite visible in rural areas such as remote areas.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] This is because small and medium-sized construction companies have technology, but they lack the capital to build large complexes in large cities.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The better the location, the more expensive the apartment is, and the more expensive the apartment complex built by a large construction company and with a large number of households.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Also, even the same type of flat in the same complex is not all of the same price.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Due to problems such as the right to sunlight and prospects, the low-rise households on the first and third floors are generally the cheapest, and the higher they go, the more expensive they become.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] In addition, the price varies depending on other conditions such as the viewing area and the direction of the house, such as south, east, west, and north.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] The upper floors with a south-facing view are the most expensive.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] Apartment sales and lease prices are actually the largest and most stable assets owned by a middle-class family in Korea, symbolizing the social status of a family, which forms a class and determines life satisfaction.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/apartment] For this reason, the Korean people have no choice but to react very sensitively to apartment prices.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] A **combustible** material is a material that can burn (i.e. sustain a flame) in air under certain conditions.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] A material is **flammable** or **inflammable** if it ignites easily at room temperature.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] In other words, a combustible material takes more effort to ignite and a flammable material ignites almost immediately when exposed to a flame.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The degree of flammability in air depends largely on how easy the material vaporizes.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] This is related to its composition-specific vapor pressure, which is temperature dependent.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The quantity of vapor produced can be enhanced by increasing the surface area of the material, forming a mist or dust.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Finely divided wood dust can undergo explosive flames and produce a blast wave.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] A piece of paper (made from pulp) catches on fire quite easily.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] A heavy oak desk is much harder to ignite, even though the wood fibers are the same in all three materials.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Common sense, and scientific consensus until the mid-1700s, suggests that material disappears when burned, as only the ash is left.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Further scientific research has found that conservation of mass holds for chemical reactions.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The burning of a solid material may appear to lose mass if the mass of combustion gases (such as carbon dioxide and water vapor) is not taken into account.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The original mass of flammable material and the mass of the oxygen consumed (from the surrounding air) equals the mass of the flame products (ash, water, carbon dioxide, and other gases).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Some metals gain mass when they burn to support the idea (because those chemical reactions capture oxygen atoms into solid compounds rather than gaseous water).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Historically, *flammable*, *inflammable* and *combustible* meant *capable of burning*.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The word "inflammable" came through French from the Latin *inflammāre* = "to set fire to", where the Latin preposition "in-" means "in" as in "indoctrinate", rather than "not" as in "invisible" and "ineligible".
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The word inflammable may be erroneously thought to mean non-flammable.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The erroneous usage of the word inflammable is a significant safety hazard.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Therefore, since the 1950s, efforts to use flammable in place of inflammable were accepted by linguists, and it is now the accepted standard in American English and British English.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Antonyms of flammable or inflammable include: *non-flammable*, *non-inflammable*, *incombustible*, *non-combustible*, *not flammable*, and *fireproof*.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Globally Harmonized System of Classification and Labelling of Chemicals uses a four category system to classify flammable liquids using flash point and boiling point temperature.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] This system is used internationally to evaluate and sort substances in industrial applications, workplaces and products distributed to consumers.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Prior to 2012, OSHA's classification of flammable and combustible liquids in regulation CFR 1910.106, was nearly identical to the National Fire Protection Association (NFPA) *Flammable and Combustible Liquids Code*, NFPA 30.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] While no longer used for occupational regulations, NFPA 30's definitions are still commonly used in fire codes and NFPA codes and standards.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Other systems for classifications of flammable liquids exist for more specialized applications, such as NFPA 704, which uses five categories.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] This is intended for emergency workers to understand the hazard posed by a substance during an emergency, such as a spill.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Flammability of furniture is of concern as cigarettes and candle accidents can trigger domestic fires.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] In 1975, California began implementing Technical Bulletin 117 (TB 117), which required that materials such as polyurethane foam used to fill furniture be able to withstand a small open flame, equivalent to a candle, for at least 12 seconds.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] In polyurethane foam, furniture manufacturers typically meet TB 117 with additive halogenated organic flame retardants.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] No other U.S. states had similar standards.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] California had such a large market, manufacturers meet TB 117 in products that they distribute across the United States.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The proliferation of flame retardants, especially halogenated organic flame retardants, in furniture across the United States is strongly linked to TB 117.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Governor Jerry Brown signed the modified TB117-2013, which became effective in 2014.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Lightweight textiles with porous surfaces are the most flammable fabrics.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Wool is less flammable than cotton, linen, silk, or viscose (rayon).
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Polyester and nylon resist ignition and melt rather than catch fire.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Acrylic is the most flammable synthetic fiber.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] A fire test can be conducted to determine the degree of flammability.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Substances with low combustibility may be selected for construction where the fire risk must be reduced, such as apartment buildings, houses, or offices.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] If combustible resources are used there is greater chance of fire accidents and deaths.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Fire resistant substances are preferred for building materials and furnishings.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] A non-combustible material is a substance that does not ignite, burn, support combustion, or release flammable vapors when subject to fire or heat.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Any solid substance complying with either of two sets of passing criteria, listed in Section 8 of ASTM E 136 when the substance is tested in accordance with the procedure specified in ASTM E 136, is considered to be non-combustible.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] A number of industrial processes produce combustible dust as a by-product.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] There are at least 140 known substances that produce combustible dust.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] While the particles in a combustible dusts may be of any size, normally they have a diameter of less than 420 μm.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] As of 2012, the United States Occupational Safety and Health Administration has yet to adopt a comprehensive set of rules on combustible dust.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] When suspended in air (or any oxidizing environment), the fine particles of combustible dust present a potential for explosions.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Accumulated dust, even when not suspended in air, remains a fire hazard.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The National Fire Protection Association (U.S.) specifically addresses the prevention of fires and dust explosions in agricultural and food products facilities in NFPA Code section 61, and other industries in NFPA Code sections 651–664.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Collectors designed to reduce airborne dust account for more than 40 percent of all dust explosions.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Other important processes are grinding and pulverizing, transporting powders, filing silos and containers (which produces powder), and the mixing and blending of powders.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Investigation of 200 dust explosions and fires, between 1980 and 2005, indicated approximately **100 fatalities and 600 injuries**.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] In January 2003, a polyethylene powder explosion and fire at the West Pharmaceutical Services plant in Kinston, North Carolina resulted in the deaths of six workers and injuries to 38 others.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] In February 2008, an explosion of sugar dust occurred at the Imperial Sugar Company's plant at Port Wentworth, Georgia, resulting in thirteen deaths.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] A flammable material storage cabinet, shown closed and open.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The design of the cabinet prevents a fire inside the cabinet from escaping outside.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] A material's flash point is a metric of how easy it is to ignite the vapor of the material as it evaporates into the atmosphere.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] It is defined as the lowest material temperature required for fuel oils in the materials to begin to give off flammable vapors in a quantity high enough to support a flash of fire when ignited by an external source.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] A lower flash point indicates higher flammability.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Materials with flash points below 100 °F (38 °C) are regulated in the United States by OSHA as potential workplace hazards.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The *flame point* of a material is a temperature value at which sustained flame can be supported on the material once ignited by an external source.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Once the flame point of a material is reached, it produces enough fuel vapors or oils to support continuous burning.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The *lower flammability limit* or *lower explosive limit (LFL/LEL)* represents the lowest air to fuel vapor concentration required for combustion to take place when ignited by an external source, for any chemical.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Any concentration lower than this could not produce a flame or result in combustion.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The *upper flammability limit* or *upper explosive limit* (UFL/UEL) represents the highest air to fuel vapor concentration at which combustion can take place when ignited by an external source.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Any fuel-air mixture higher than this would be too concentrated to result in combustion.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The values existing between these two limits represent the flammable or explosive range.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Within this threshold, given an external ignition source, combustion of the particular fuel would likely happen.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The vapor pressure of a liquid is a measure of how much the vapor of the liquid tends to concentrate in the surrounding atmosphere as the liquid evaporates.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Vapor pressure is a major determinant of the flash point and flame point, with higher vapor pressures leading to lower flash points and higher flammability ratings.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The International Code Council (ICC) developed fire code requirements to provide adequate protection to a building and its occupants.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] These codes specify the combustibility rating for materials, the entrance and exit requirements, active fire protection requirements, and numerous other things.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] In the U.S., other agencies have also developed building codes that specify combustibility ratings.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Following the requirements of these fire codes is crucial for higher occupancy buildings.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] For existing buildings, fire codes focus on maintaining the occupancies as originally intended.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] In other words, if a portion of a building were designed as an apartment, one could not suddenly load it with flammable liquids and turn it into a gas storage facility.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The fire load and smoke development in that one apartment would be so immense it would overtax the active and passive fire protection means for the building.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] The handling and use of flammable substances inside a building is subject to the local fire code, which is enforced by the local fire prevention officer.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Understanding combustibility and flammability is important for fire service operations.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Flammable materials, like gasoline, produce vapors that can ignite at low temperatures.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] This can contribute to rapid fire spread, even to remote locations.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Combustible materials, like wood, require a higher temperature to ignite, but will burn longer once it reaches that temperature.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Knowing what materials are present in a building is very important for firefighters.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Knowing whether a material is flammable or combustible can help firefighters know what to expect as far as fire behavior and how quickly the fire may spread.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Buildings with flammable liquids or gases would be at a higher risk for a quick growing fire with a lot of heat early on.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Buildings storing combustibles may have a lower rate of spread, but can sustain burning longer.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] There are many different factors that influence how materials will burn.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Moisture, surface area, and the ventilation in the area are a few factors, as well as, flash points and ignition temperatures.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Armed with knowledge like the flash point and whether it is considered flammable or combustible helps firefighters predict fire behavior and use the correct suppression methods.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Various countries have tests for determining non-combustibility of materials.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Most involve the heating of a specified quantity of the test specimen for a set duration.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Usually, the material must not support combustion and must not lose more than a specified amount of mass.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] As a general rule of thumb, concrete, steel, and ceramics - in other words inorganic substances - pass these tests.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Building codes list them as suitable and sometimes mandate their use in certain applications.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] In Canada, for instance, firewalls must be made of concrete.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] Materials can be tested for the degree of flammability and combustibility in accordance with the German DIN 4102.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] DIN 4102, as well as its British cousin BS 476 include for testing of passive fire protection systems, as well as some of its constituent materials.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] A more recent industrial standard is the European EN 13501-1 - Fire classification of construction products and building elements—which roughly replaces A2 with A2/B, B1 with C, B2 with D/E and B3 with F.
[src:combustibility-and-flammability/combustibility-and-flammability] B3 or F rated materials may not be used in building unless combined with another material that reduces the flammability of those materials.
